WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:14.620
Good day, everybody. Last year I was at the RStudio conference as well, and several questions

00:00:14.620 --> 00:00:19.840
have been addressed about tidy time series analysis during the conference, especially

00:00:19.840 --> 00:00:27.639
forecasting with tidy objects. So today I'm going to present a solution to that. So I

00:00:27.639 --> 00:00:33.160
want to talk about a streamlined workflow for time series under the Tidyverse framework

00:00:33.160 --> 00:00:39.520
using two packages. I introduce you three big ideas behind those two packages. So they

00:00:39.520 --> 00:00:45.799
are Sible, Mable, and Fable, and how they link together. I hope to explain them concretely

00:00:45.799 --> 00:00:52.240
with data stories. So I believe this diagram isn't foreign to you. This is a Tidyverse

00:00:52.240 --> 00:00:57.959
model, and each module here is powered by one of the Tidyverse packages. And the Tidyverse

00:00:57.959 --> 00:01:03.480
plays seamlessly with each other, and one of the fundamental reasons is they all share

00:01:03.480 --> 00:01:10.360
the same underlying data structure, which is data frame or a table. So the data is actually

00:01:10.360 --> 00:01:16.519
placed in the center of the diagram. But why we cannot bring this workflow easily into

00:01:16.519 --> 00:01:25.480
time series? So because the current time series objects in R are model-focused. By

00:01:25.480 --> 00:01:31.080
saying model, I mean it not only includes statistical models, but also forecasting,

00:01:31.080 --> 00:01:37.040
decomposition, autocorrelation function, and other time series tools. And all the methods

00:01:37.040 --> 00:01:43.279
or functions expect matrices as inputs. But the data arrives in the right beginning of

00:01:43.279 --> 00:01:49.279
this process. It really comes into the matrix form. And we have to write so much ad hoc

00:01:49.279 --> 00:01:58.839
code to get the data into a time series model-ready object. It is a pain because of the mismatch

00:01:58.839 --> 00:02:07.320
between temporal data and time series models. So we hope to change that. So some new tools

00:02:07.320 --> 00:02:13.039
are provided to streamline this workflow and make time series analysis a bit easier, more

00:02:13.039 --> 00:02:18.199
fun, and more intuitive. So the Sibyl package will focus on the tidy and transformation

00:02:18.199 --> 00:02:23.800
part. The Fable package will do time series forecasting, and the visualization is done

00:02:23.800 --> 00:02:30.000
with ggplot2 and its extensions. So to make this workflow work, they're going to share

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:36.080
the same underlying data structure, which is a new data abstraction for time series,

00:02:36.080 --> 00:02:43.720
and we call it Sibyl. So Sibyl is a time series table, and if you know TS is a native

00:02:43.720 --> 00:02:52.119
object to represent time series in R, so this is where the name Sibyl comes from. So now

00:02:52.119 --> 00:02:57.759
we are going to have some fun with the open data set. So this data set is about residential

00:02:57.759 --> 00:03:04.039
electricity consumption in Australia. So it's a table with 46 million observations and eight

00:03:04.039 --> 00:03:11.240
variables. So the column custom ID includes unique identifiers for each household, thousands

00:03:11.240 --> 00:03:17.360
of households in this data set, and a rating date time gives the time stamps when the rating

00:03:17.360 --> 00:03:24.880
is recorded every 30 minutes. General supply is a variable that we are interested in forecasting,

00:03:24.880 --> 00:03:29.399
and there are some other measurements in the table as well. So first, how are we going

00:03:29.399 --> 00:03:38.639
to turn this data into a Sibyl? So what makes time series special or different from a normal

00:03:38.639 --> 00:03:45.440
data frame? Because it has its own semantics. So the first one is obviously the index variable

00:03:45.440 --> 00:03:52.039
that represents time. So in this case, it's rating date time, and Sibyl supports a wide

00:03:52.039 --> 00:03:58.520
range of time classes, so for numerics to date time to nano time. So the second component

00:03:58.520 --> 00:04:04.600
is what we call key, and the identifying variables that define series or entities

00:04:04.600 --> 00:04:10.679
over time. For this example, each household is a series, and the key variable is custom

00:04:10.679 --> 00:04:17.480
ID. You can also include multiple variables in the key. So basically, index defines the

00:04:17.480 --> 00:04:24.399
time and the key defines the series. So the key together with index uniquely identifies

00:04:24.399 --> 00:04:31.040
each observation in a Sibyl. Basically, it means each customer has to have unique time

00:04:31.040 --> 00:04:38.040
stamps, and for this data, yes, they are. So now we have a Sibyl. So Sibyl gives a very

00:04:38.040 --> 00:04:44.799
nice printing method, and Sibyl is going to enhance that by adding contextual information.

00:04:44.799 --> 00:04:50.600
So now we have a Sibyl with data dimensions, and it recognizes 30 minutes interval, and

00:04:50.600 --> 00:04:57.320
the time zone associated with the index. So here, we have UTC, but you might have time

00:04:57.320 --> 00:05:02.920
zones with daylight savings, for example, and Sibyl will respect any time zone in your

00:05:02.920 --> 00:05:11.920
data. So the key variable is reported with a number of the series, so we have 2,924 customers

00:05:11.920 --> 00:05:19.799
in this big table. And we also got some time gaps in this data, so there are implicit missing

00:05:19.799 --> 00:05:26.600
values. Since ggplot2 isn't aware of those gaps, it always draws a straight line between

00:05:26.600 --> 00:05:32.399
data segments if you use geomline, and Sibyl comes with a very handy function called fill

00:05:32.399 --> 00:05:40.559
gaps, so it fills in those gaps with NA by default, or you can do by values or functions.

00:05:40.559 --> 00:05:47.760
So those lines can be removed from the plot easily with fill gaps. So except for fill

00:05:47.880 --> 00:05:54.119
gaps, Sibyl provides other three verbs to handle implicit missing values, and they all

00:05:54.119 --> 00:06:01.839
suffix by gaps. So nearly 20% of the customers have time gaps, and the output shown here,

00:06:01.839 --> 00:06:07.600
you can see the last two customers with gaps. So almost all the model functions require

00:06:07.600 --> 00:06:14.200
complete time series, so it's a good practice to look at and fill in those gaps in the first

00:06:14.279 --> 00:06:24.279
place. So Sibyl works nicely with deplier and tidier verbs. A new end verb you will

00:06:24.279 --> 00:06:31.040
use quite often is index by. So it's similar to group by by preparing grouping structure,

00:06:31.040 --> 00:06:36.600
but it only groups the index. So combined with summarize, the data can be aggregated

00:06:36.600 --> 00:06:43.000
to any high-level time resolutions. So for example, I want to work with hourly data instead

00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:49.880
of 30 minutes, and I use floor date, or selling date, or run date from the looped package

00:06:49.880 --> 00:06:56.279
on the index variable inside the index by, followed by a summarize. So I get hourly average

00:06:56.279 --> 00:07:01.959
electricity usage across all the households. So the result is going to be a single time

00:07:01.959 --> 00:07:10.760
series and one hour interval, and the key is implicit. So another chunk of operations

00:07:10.760 --> 00:07:17.519
for time series is definitely rolling window, and it not only does iteration over each element,

00:07:17.519 --> 00:07:25.239
like what per map does, but also needs to roll. So what I'm going to do is to wake up

00:07:25.239 --> 00:07:36.399
this cat and let her roll. So actually there are three different types of rolling operations,

00:07:36.399 --> 00:07:43.119
so sliding, tiling, and stretching. So it's just like per, slide takes one input, slide

00:07:43.119 --> 00:07:50.720
two takes two inputs, and p-slide for multiples. So if you have a data frame to roll by observations,

00:07:50.720 --> 00:07:55.880
you need to use p-slide, and for the purpose of type stability, they're going to return

00:07:55.880 --> 00:08:03.000
a list. And other variants include like integers, characters, logicals, et cetera. So in the

00:08:03.000 --> 00:08:08.959
recent version, I've added the parallel support. They're all prefixed with future by using

00:08:08.959 --> 00:08:14.600
the fir package by Davis as a backend. So if you're doing some rolling regressions,

00:08:14.600 --> 00:08:20.200
so it's nice to save some time by rolling them in parallel. And you can put an arbitrary

00:08:20.200 --> 00:08:27.679
function through those rolling windows. So a simple example is rolling average. It uses

00:08:27.679 --> 00:08:33.880
parallel syntax, so you can call a function name or an anonymous function using tilde.

00:08:33.880 --> 00:08:40.080
I specify the window size to be 24, so basically one day, and it's rolling forward from left

00:08:40.080 --> 00:08:45.000
to right. If you want to move in an opposite direction, just change the window size to

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:53.400
be negative. So those three rolling windows, as you can see, result different averages.

00:08:53.400 --> 00:08:59.559
A more advanced example but extremely useful is rolling forecast. So I defined a custom

00:08:59.559 --> 00:09:07.559
function called expand forecast and also enable parallel processing by using future p-stretch.

00:09:07.559 --> 00:09:13.359
It's never been that easy to do an expanding forecasting on. So a nice thing about functional

00:09:13.359 --> 00:09:20.359
programming is we can focus on writing expressions instead of writing a long for loop statement.

00:09:20.479 --> 00:09:25.919
So what sort of code goes into the expand forecast? And this question brings us to the

00:09:25.919 --> 00:09:32.599
next part of the presentation, tidy forecasting. So how many of you have used the forecast

00:09:32.599 --> 00:09:40.200
package before? Quite a lot. Thank you. So the Fable is a tidy replacement of the forecast

00:09:40.320 --> 00:09:47.320
package. So why we call it Fable? First, it makes forecasting tables. Second, a Fable

00:09:50.760 --> 00:09:57.760
is like a forecast. It's never true, but it tells you something useful. So let's take

00:09:59.559 --> 00:10:06.359
a look at the data in the first 30 days of January. So each facet gives a daily snapshot

00:10:06.359 --> 00:10:11.760
of hourly electricity demand. And the peak in the late afternoon is driven by the use

00:10:11.760 --> 00:10:17.719
of air conditioning. And January is the summertime in Australia. So you can see some days have

00:10:17.719 --> 00:10:23.559
much higher usage, colored by red, because they are very hot days with maximum temperature

00:10:23.559 --> 00:10:29.840
greater than 32 degrees. And I'm going to use this subset to forecast the demand one

00:10:29.840 --> 00:10:36.840
day ahead. And I hold the data of January 31 as a test set. So let's model the data.

00:10:40.479 --> 00:10:47.479
So I construct two models for the energy consumption with a model verb. And the first model I built

00:10:48.239 --> 00:10:54.880
is a naive model as a benchmark. So the naive method simply uses the observed values from

00:10:54.880 --> 00:11:01.640
yesterday as forecasts. And the second model is ETS, exponential smoothing, which can be

00:11:01.640 --> 00:11:08.520
thought of as a weighted average of the past values. And ETS is also short for error, trend,

00:11:08.520 --> 00:11:15.400
and seasonality. So the model function uses a formula interface. So on the left-hand side,

00:11:15.400 --> 00:11:20.880
we specify the average supply as a response variable. And on the right-hand side, we can

00:11:20.880 --> 00:11:27.880
put some specials related to the method. So I've specified the naive function to use the 24

00:11:28.479 --> 00:11:34.520
values from yesterday instead of the value from the previous hour. And if we don't specify

00:11:34.520 --> 00:11:40.799
the right-hand side like ETS, so it will do automatic model selection by picking up the

00:11:40.799 --> 00:11:47.760
best model for you. So now we have a Mabel back. So a Mabel is a model table that contains

00:11:47.760 --> 00:11:54.760
model objects. So each cell shows a succinct model representation saying I have a seasonal

00:11:55.679 --> 00:12:02.679
naive model and an ETS with three selected components. So models are reduced form of

00:12:03.919 --> 00:12:10.919
the data. So the model function is an analog of summarize because they use the same semantics.

00:12:11.440 --> 00:12:17.880
And the model function also reduces the data down to a single summary, but it happens to

00:12:17.880 --> 00:12:24.880
be a model object of that summary. So in order to look at like parameter estimates, information

00:12:28.080 --> 00:12:34.919
criteria, or residuals from model objects, we just use a familiar Bloom functions, tidy,

00:12:34.919 --> 00:12:40.559
glance, and augment. By applying the tidy function on the Mabel, we get the parameter

00:12:40.559 --> 00:12:47.559
estimates for the models we've built. So we've got a bunch of parameters for ETS, like alpha,

00:12:47.760 --> 00:12:54.760
beta, and I know those are boring parameters. So it's time to forecast. We pipe the Mabel

00:12:56.080 --> 00:13:02.000
into the forecast function, and we're doing a one-day-ahead forecast, equivalent to 24

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:07.559
steps ahead. And it supports human-friendly input, so we can read more naturally, like

00:13:07.559 --> 00:13:13.760
forecasting with one-day horizon. It's convenient because we no longer need to mentally compute

00:13:13.760 --> 00:13:19.719
how many hours, minutes, seconds in a day, but it can still do H equal to 24. And we're

00:13:19.719 --> 00:13:26.039
done with forecasts. We have a forecasting table, which is a fable. So it's a special

00:13:26.039 --> 00:13:31.719
table, which includes the future predictions. It not only tells you the point forecasts,

00:13:31.719 --> 00:13:36.919
but also our underlying prediction distribution that involves uncertainty, because we are

00:13:36.919 --> 00:13:43.039
forecasters, not fortune tellers. And you can see the normal distribution with its mean

00:13:43.039 --> 00:13:48.239
and standard deviation in the last column dot distribution. And this is one of my favorite

00:13:48.239 --> 00:13:54.359
features about Fable, reporting distribution forecasts. So you're able to produce any level

00:13:54.359 --> 00:14:00.119
of prediction interval you like. And we'll see the forecast more clearly with plots

00:14:00.119 --> 00:14:07.119
using geom forecast. So the naive method repeats yesterday's pattern, but the 80 and 95 predictions

00:14:08.119 --> 00:14:15.119
intervals are quite large, and some even goes below zero. So how about ATS? So the ATS nicely

00:14:15.559 --> 00:14:21.599
captures the daily trend and produces a much narrower prediction interval. And which model

00:14:21.599 --> 00:14:28.280
performs better? So use the accuracy function to compare the predictions with a test set

00:14:28.280 --> 00:14:33.840
that I held before. So looking at the accuracy measures, ATS does slightly better than the

00:14:33.840 --> 00:14:40.479
naive in terms of root mean squared error. But they all tend to give underestimated predictions.

00:14:40.479 --> 00:14:47.239
And the black line in the plot is actual data. So it looks like it's another hot day in January.

00:14:47.239 --> 00:14:52.719
If we have weather information like temperatures, we can include them to improve the forecast,

00:14:52.719 --> 00:14:57.880
but need to use a different model that allows for exogenous regressors. For example, a Ramer

00:14:57.880 --> 00:15:04.000
model. So far, I have showed all the steps from model building to model assessments for

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:10.280
just one time series. Would it be any different if we have multiple time series in a table?

00:15:10.280 --> 00:15:16.119
No, because models are fundamentally scalable. So it's simple as a modern reimagining of

00:15:16.119 --> 00:15:21.520
time series. It designs for hosting many time series together. Especially the series

00:15:21.520 --> 00:15:26.799
have already been defined when we created the table. And we are obviously interested

00:15:26.799 --> 00:15:33.000
in forecasting the demands for each household here. So I've removed some troublesome series,

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:40.000
ended up with 1,480 households. So no extra steps needed for forecasting and scale. Just

00:15:40.599 --> 00:15:45.960
as what we did before, we can directly pipe them into the model function. It will fit

00:15:45.960 --> 00:15:52.960
an ETS model for each customer at once, and then happy forecast. So I also take a log

00:15:53.919 --> 00:15:59.919
transformation on the response variable to ensure that I get positive forecast back.

00:15:59.919 --> 00:16:05.520
And the forecast function will take care of the back transformation for you. So you can

00:16:05.520 --> 00:16:12.520
see 1,480 models have been faded in the Mabel. And the key variable is always a key to refer

00:16:12.880 --> 00:16:19.640
to a series across Siebel, Mabel, and Fabel. Models are scalable, but visualization is

00:16:19.640 --> 00:16:26.280
not. So I just plot four customers with their forecast here. And the individual level, lots

00:16:26.280 --> 00:16:33.280
of noise, producing much larger prediction interval as well. So I've shown a proportion

00:16:33.280 --> 00:16:39.960
of what Siebel and Fabel can do. We've got decomposition simulation based on model fades,

00:16:39.960 --> 00:16:45.520
interpolation of missing values, and model supports for streaming data. So please check

00:16:45.520 --> 00:16:52.520
them out. So it's a joint work with Di Cook, Rob Hyman, and Mitch O'Hara-Wild.

00:16:54.640 --> 00:16:59.320
I need to mention that Siebel is on Chrome, but Fabel is on GitHub at the moment. And

00:16:59.320 --> 00:17:06.239
they all belong to tidyverts.org. Those are the useful links to those packages, my slides,

00:17:06.239 --> 00:17:13.239
and the source code behind the slides. That's all from me. Thank you.

00:17:13.239 --> 00:17:20.239
Thank you so much, Eero. We have time for a couple of questions, and we have throwable

00:17:22.760 --> 00:17:27.760
mics moving around, so just raise your hand.

00:17:27.760 --> 00:17:34.760
Hello? Can you hear me? Okay. I'm wondering if any of these tools are well-suited for

00:17:36.959 --> 00:17:39.280
irregular time series?

00:17:39.280 --> 00:17:40.079
Not yet.

00:17:40.079 --> 00:17:40.640
Okay.

00:17:40.640 --> 00:17:45.640
But Siebel will support irregular data structure.

00:17:45.640 --> 00:17:51.640
Hi. I was wondering if this supports hierarchical time series, reconciliation?

00:17:51.640 --> 00:17:58.640
Yes, we're considering that probably second half of this year.

00:18:06.239 --> 00:18:13.239
What is the level of maturity of the package with compare the models that are available

00:18:15.599 --> 00:18:18.920
today in the forecast package?

00:18:18.920 --> 00:18:25.359
So we sort of like think go to Chrome like sometime in March or April, and if like to

00:18:25.359 --> 00:18:32.359
replace the whole forecast package would be like the end of this year, I think.

00:18:33.359 --> 00:18:39.199
I noticed that there's a rival Tyble time package, and I'm just wondering what the difference

00:18:39.199 --> 00:18:43.719
between Siebel and Tyble time is.

00:18:43.719 --> 00:18:50.280
So basically there's two time series structures, and we've got a couple of things in common.

00:18:50.280 --> 00:18:57.239
So first, both are built on top of Tyble, and second, both declare the index variable,

00:18:57.359 --> 00:19:03.599
and for Siebel, we require the key as well, and also does the check, so it needs to be

00:19:03.599 --> 00:19:06.160
distinctive observations.

00:19:06.160 --> 00:19:12.760
So this makes Siebel is different from Tyble time, and also the function like interface

00:19:12.760 --> 00:19:15.040
are also different.

00:19:15.040 --> 00:19:20.040
Do I answer your question?

00:19:20.040 --> 00:19:27.040
I think we have time for one more question.

00:19:28.239 --> 00:19:31.839
I love these things.

00:19:31.839 --> 00:19:36.280
So kind of a shoot off of the last question, do you have any plans to incorporate the ability

00:19:36.280 --> 00:19:42.119
to specify time windows using shorthand like XTS does or like Tyble time does?

00:19:42.119 --> 00:19:46.199
Yes, I do have the functions.

00:19:46.199 --> 00:19:51.199
It's called a filter underscore index, so it does support the shorthand.

00:19:51.199 --> 00:19:53.520
Just to check the documentation, please.

